    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>This post describes the process necessary to install and configure rtorrent on a remote machine running <a href="http://www.ubuntu.com/">Ubuntu</a> or <a href="http://linuxmint.com/">Mint</a>. I need to document this process for my own use, because it took me longer to setup that it should have and I don't want to have to repeat that experience. I want to thank <a href="http://randystech.com/">Randy</a> for his init.d script.</p>

<!-- more -->


<h2>Assumptions</h2>

<p>You are familiar with basic Linux concepts such as sudo, home directory, opening terminal windows and entering shell commands.</p>

<h2>Motivation</h2>

<p>For a while now I have been running Windows + utorrent. Recently we installed a 100Mb/40Mb fibre link, so I thought I would setup a spare netbook as an always switched on seedbox. Then I would have not to leave my desktop running overnight, as it is a power hungry beast.</p>

<p>I also wanted a fire and forget torrent solution. One that pickups .torrent files from a watch directory, download them and then seed them to a certain ratio.</p>

<h2>Prequisites</h2>

<p>Fresh install of <a href="http://linuxmint.com/">Linux Mint</a> on the emachine. That will be our starting point.</p>

<h2>Step 1 - Configure Router</h2>

<p>I had this step last, but unless you know how to do this, then there is no point in doing the other steps. A lot of GUI torrent clients have uPNP support,which means that the torrent client speaks to your router and says please ma'am can you open a port for me. But I'm not able to say if rtorrent has uPNP support, so I open ports on my router manually. As router configuration is model specific, all I can tell you is you need to forward port range 60125-64125 for TCP traffic to the IP address of the machine on which rtorrent is running.</p>

<h2>Step 2 - Install required Packages</h2>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>sudo apt-get -y install rtorrent</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<h2>Step 3 - Create required Folders</h2>

<p>Create the following folders, the ~ character in shell command below indicates my home directory. You can call the directories any names you want. The important thing is you create one directory where rtorrent will download files into (~/pirate/incoming) and one directory which rtorrent will watch (~/pirate/watch). When you place a .torrent file in the watch directory rtorrent will automatically load it.</p>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>mkdir -p ~/pirate/incoming
</span><span class='line'>mkdir -p ~/pirate/watch</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<h2>Step 4 - Create Configuration File</h2>

<p>In this step you will create a file that rtorrent reads configuration information from. Create in your home directory a file called .rtorrent.rc and paste the following in. The only changes you should need to make are to directory names if you changed them from what I used above (eg Lines 6,8)</p>

